This paper discusses bibliometric indices and their application in evaluating research output and impact. The paper focuses on the field of physics, but the concepts and methods discussed are applicable to many fields, including computer science. The paper proposes a two-dimensional index that measures both the output and outreach of an individual's research, which could be relevant to many sub-categories of computer science. The paper does not focus on a specific sub-category of computer science, but the concepts discussed are relevant to several sub-categories, including digital libraries (cs.DL), information retrieval (cs.IR), social and information networks (cs.SI), cryptography and security (cs.CR), and computers and society (cs.CY).
